│ 507   // Handling expressions which produce invariant results, but          │
│ *haven't* yet                                                               │
│ 508   // been removed from the loop serves two important purposes.          │
│ 509   // 1) Most importantly, it resolves a pass ordering cycle which would │
│ 510   // otherwise need us to iteration licm, loop-predication, and either  │
│ 511   // loop-unswitch or loop-peeling to make progress on examples with    │
│ lots of                                                                     │
│ 512   // predicable range checks in a row.  (Since, in the general case,    │
│ we can't                                                                    │
│ 513   // hoist the length checks until the dominating checks have been      │
│ discharged                                                                  │
│ 514   // as we can't prove doing so is safe.)                               │
│ 515   // 2) As a nice side effect, this exposes the value of peeling or     │
│ unswitching                                                                 │
│ 516   // much more obviously in the IR.  Otherwise, the cost modeling for   │
│ other                                                                       │
│ 517   // transforms would end up needing to duplicate all of this logic to  │
│ model a                                                                     │
│ 518   // check which becomes predictable based on a modeled peel or         │
│ unswitch.                                                                   │
│ 519   //                                                                    │
│ 520   // The cost of doing so in the worst case is an extra fill from the   │
│ stack  in                                                                   │
│ 521   // the loop to materialize the loop invariant test value instead of   │
│ checking                                                                    │
│ 522   // against the original IV which is presumable in a register inside   │
│ the loop.                                                                   │
│ 523   // Such cases are presumably rare, and hint at missing oppurtunities  │
│ for                                                                         │
│ 524   // other passes.                                                      │
│ 525                                                                         │
│ 526   if (SE->isLoopInvariant(S, L))                                        │
│ 527     // Note: This the SCEV variant, so the original Value* may be       │
│ within the                                                                  │
│ 528     // loop even though SCEV has proven it is loop invariant.           │
